@Node "PSM_What is it?" "PGP_MIP.guide/PSM_What is it?"
@Next "PSM_Installation"
@Toc "PGPSendMail"

What is PGPSendMail?
====================

    PGPSendMail is a small tool, to automatically encrypt your outgoing
e-mail. Despite the name, PGPSendMail does @{i}not@{ui} handle any UUCP stuff,
but needs the original sendmail to be in town.

    PGPSendMail scans through the outgoing mail and checks if a public
key is available for the receipient(s). (1) If a key is available, a
requester will pop up, asking you if you'd like to encrypt the mail.
When you choose the "yes" gadget, the message-body will be encrypted
and the result will be sent to sendmail to handle the UUCP-stuff.

The encrypted message will look something like this:

     Automatically encrypted message-body follows:
     
     -----BEGIN PGP MESSAGE-----
     Version: 2.3a
     
     owHrZAhlYmXUqV9ctnnP/pPtVcsSGRm3aDEx7G1+9enVmcr3Ff5GfN6fdKde2Zau
     X3kjdonMydeTi4zuvlDZH/sia1O/ZYKDsAGXt+K+0lVOyvx9h3Yc2hUkoFXGor4m
     uoSlJLW4hAEIPFIrFXIT83QUUvLz1EsUKvNLFTISy1IVivNzU0syMvPSFZJSS0pS
     ixRK8oFKdBRKMhLzQOzkosTkbLAqXq7k/JTUYnsFK11NTV4uAA==
     =y7/l
     -----END PGP MESSAGE-----

How does it work?
=================

    PGPSendMail has to be called instead of sendmail, so it gets it
hands on the message first. PGPSendMail then finds out the receipients
(2) and checks if a public key is available for each of them. (3) Then
PGPSendMail saves the message-body to a temporary file and encrypts it,
using the keys of the receipients. Afterwards, the encrypted copy is
sent to sendmail, using exactly the same commandline PGPSendMail has
been called with. (4)

    If @{i}any@{ui} error occurs, PGPSendMail will immediatly stop his
processing and will call sendmail to handle the unencrypted mails, to
prevent data-loss.

    ---------- Footnotes ----------

    (1)  Multiple receipients via @{b}To:@{ub} or @{b}Cc:@{ub} are supported. @{b}Bcc:@{ub} will
be supported in a future release.

    (2)  PGPSendMail does alias expansion using @{b}UULIB:Aliases@{ub}.

    (3)  Currently PGPSendMail does not handle the situation, that a
few keys are available and a few not.  See @{"Future releases" Link "PSM_Future releases"}. It will @{i}not@{ui}
encrypt the message, even if only ones key is missing.

    (4)  This should avoid any problems with different sendmail
versions.


@EndNode

@Node "PSM_Installation" "PGP_MIP.guide/PSM_Installation"
@Next "PSM_Configuration"
@Prev "PSM_What is it?"
@Toc "PGPSendMail"

How to install PGPSendMail into your UUCP site:
===============================================

The Installation of PGPSendMail is pretty simple:

   - First of all, copy @{b}PGPSendMail/PGPSendMail@{ub} somewhere into your
     command path, usually @{b}UUCPC:@{ub} or @{b}UUCP:c/@{ub}.

   - Configure you mail reader to call PGPSendMail instead of sendmail,
     @{i}but just change the name of the program, leave the options and
     parameters alone@{ui}. (1)

     With AmigaELM this would be something like this:
          SendMail        pgpsendmail <$MSG -f foobar

     @{i}ATTENTION:@{ui} Do NOT change the @{b}RMail@{ub}-entry in your UUCP master
     config file (2) to call pgpsendmail. Leave them to the normal
     sendmail, or you machine will try to encrypt any mail routed
     through your system.

   - Now generate a listing of your keyring, calling @{b}PGP -kvv
     >UULIB:PGPKeys.lst@{ub} so PGPSendMail can determine wether a public key
     for a certain receipient is available. See @{"Future releases" Link "PSM_Future releases"}.

   - If you haven't set @{i}PGPPASS@{ui} yet, the time has come to do so, or
     PGPSendMail won't be able to encrypt anything. Please read PGP's
     manual for further details on @{i}PGPPASS@{ui}. See @{"Future releases" Link "PSM_Future releases"}.

     @{i}ATTENTION:@{ui} You have to generate this list using the @{b}-kvv@{ub} command,
     or PGPSendMail won't recognize the @{b}also known as ...@{ub} feature of
     PGP.

    That's all! Now, every outgoing mail will be routed through
PGPSendMail and will be encrypted and signed if a key for the
receipient is available. (3)

    If your system has enough memory, you should make PGP and
PGPSendMail resident, what should result in a significant speedup.

    If you have only a small amount of spare memory, you may assign @{b}T:@{ub}
to your harddisk (4), because all temporary file are created in the
@{b}T:@{ub}-directory. This would save some memory, while slowing your
system down.

    ---------- Footnotes ----------

    (1)  In fact you have to change this in any program that has the
capability to send e-mails! This may include your newsreader, too.

    (2)  @{b}UULIB:Config@{ub} or @{b}S:UUConfig@{ub}

    (3)  Public keys with undefined validity won't be used for
encryption unless you have used them by hand once.  Then PGP will
assume you trust these keys at least a little bit. :-)

    (4)  Usually, @{b}T:@{ub} is assigned somewhere in the RAM-Disk for
speed-reasons.


@EndNode

@Node "PSM_Configuration" "PGP_MIP.guide/PSM_Configuration"
@Next "PSM_Log messages"
@Prev "PSM_Installation"
@Toc "PGPSendMail"

Configurating PGPSendMail:
==========================

    Usually, PGPSendMail does @{i}not@{ui} need any configuration. However, it
checks out the following keywords in either @{b}S:UUConfig@{ub} or @{b}UULIB:Config@{ub}:

@{b}Debug@{ub}
     Here, you can set the amount of debugging output, PGPSendMail shall
     write to the logfile. The higher the number is, the more output is
     provided. Default is @{b}0@{ub}.

@{b}UULib@{ub}
     Here you can specify a directory path, where the other configfiles
     are stored. This path is required to access the @{b}Aliases@{ub} and
     @{b}PGPKeys.lst@{ub} file. Default is @{b}UULIB:@{ub}.

@{b}Lockdir@{ub}
     Here you can choose the directory, the UUCP-package shall create
     the temporary files for file-access-syncronization in. Default is
     @{b}T:@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "PSM_Log messages" "PGP_MIP.guide/PSM_Log messages"
@Next "PSM_Future releases"
@Prev "PSM_Configuration"
@Toc "PGPSendMail"

What logfile entries does PGPSendMail generate and what do they mean?
=====================================================================

    PGPSendMail logs various events, if you set @{i}Debug@{ui} to an appropiate
value (see @{"Debug" Link "PSM_Configuration"}). The required debuglevel is described. If no
debuglevel is explicitly mentioned, the log message can't be surpressed.

@{b}"original mail in <filename>"@{ub}
     The original mail is stored in this temorary file. Debuglevel 2.

@{b}"receipients (with aliases): foobar"@{ub}
     The parsing process resulted in this receipients. The aliases are
     not expanded yet. Debuglevel 2.

@{b}"receipients (aliases expanded): foobar"@{ub}
     The parsing process resulted in this receipients. The aliases are
     expanded. Debuglevel 2.

@{b}"copied message-body to <filename> for encryption"@{ub}
     The message-body has been stored in this temporary file
     successfully.  Debuglevel 2.

@{b}"copying modified mail to <filename>"@{ub}
     The "new" mail (original header plus encrypted message body) is
     stored in this temporary file. Debuglevel 2.

@{b}"starting <command>"@{ub}
     The following command is issued. Usually, this is PGP or sendmail.
     The commandline is logged, too. Debuglevel 2.

@{b}"successfully encrypted mail for <address>"@{ub}
     Everything went fine.

@{b}"No key available for <address>"@{ub}
     The encrypting process was interrupted, because this key is
     missing.  Even more keys may be missing, PGPSendMail currently
     stops if only one key can't be found. See @{"Future versions" Link "PSM_Future releases"}.
     Debuglevel 1.

@{b}"Can't open <filename>"@{ub}
     The specified file couldn't be opened.

@{b}"No Colon in line %d"@{ub}
@{b}"recursion near user <username>"@{ub}
     Some error in the alias-file has been spotted.

@{b}"Couldn't allocate my buffer!"@{ub}
     PGPSendMail was unable to allocate a buffer of the required size.

@{b}"Can't open temporary file!"@{ub}
@{b}"Can't write to my temporary file!"@{ub}
     Some access to a temporary file has failed.

@{b}"Can't determine receipient of message"@{ub}
     ParseHeaderLine() failed somehow. Please report this to the
     author, if the commandline was correct.

@{b}"Not all receipients have a valid public key"@{ub}
     Currently a fatal error. See @{"Future versions" Link "PSM_Future releases"}. Debuglevel 1.

@{b}"PGP failed somehow"@{ub}
     PGP returned an error. PGPSendMail does not check what kind of
     error occured, but uses the unmodified mail. (PGP's returncodes
     are not accurate enough to determine the reason for the error for
     shure.)

@{b}"Truncating the original failed."@{ub}
     If the encrypted message-body is shorter than the original, the
     file must be truncated, what failed.

@{b}"Buffer overflow!"@{ub}
     A buffer with a fixed size was too small for this case. Please
     report to the author.


@EndNode

@Node "PSM_Future releases" "PGP_MIP.guide/PSM_Future releases"
@Next "PSM_System requirements"
@Prev "PSM_Log messages"
@Toc "PGPSendMail"

What is planned for future version?
===================================

   - The current version of PGPSendMail does not handle mails for
     multiple receipients in the best way. @{b}Bcc:@{ub} is not supported and
     the whole process interrupts if only one key is missing. This will
     be improved in future releases.

     The next version of PGPSendMail will send the mail out in encrypted
     form for the receipients that have a key available and unencrypted
     for the rest of 'em. :-) Maybe PGPSendMail will append a note
     automatically, encouraging the key-less receipients to install PGP.

   - This version does not parse the keyring directly, but needs a
     keylist to be around. This is somewhat uncomfortable for the user,
     because he has to generate a new list every time he modifies the
     keyring. Future version will access the keyring directly.

   - PGPSendMail has to expand aliases in order to determine the
     addresses of the receipients. The alias-expansion code has been
     taken from Matt Dillon's UUCP package with slight modifications.
     But someone really has to optimize this code, because it's uh...
     horrible. (No offense Matt!)

   - Also worth improving is the way PGP is controlled by PGPSendMail.
     At the moment you need @{i}PGPPASS@{ui} (see @{"system requirements" Link "PRM_System requirements"}) set in
     order to make PGP encrypt anything. This is no real security lack,
     since PGP does support local shell variables, however, I'm
     planning to add a routine to PGPRMail, that pops up a requester
     and asks the user for the password, submitting the result to PGP
     via the commandline.

     Also I'm thinking about opening a console-window for PGP, so the
     user can see what is going on and can possibly control PGP
     interactivly.


@EndNode

@Node "PSM_System requirements" "PGP_MIP.guide/PSM_System requirements"
@Prev "PSM_Future releases"
@Toc "PGPSendMail"

What do I need to run PGPSendMail?
==================================

   - You need at least KICKSTART 2.04 to run PGPSendMail.

   - PGPSendMail works @{i}only@{ui} with PGP v2.2 or later. Earlier version
     were not able to encrypt mails for several receipients, neither
     did they have the @{b}+batchmode@{ub} feature.

   - You must have @{b}T:@{ub} assigned, because all temporary files go into @{b}T:@{ub}.

   - The original "sendmail" @{i}must@{ui} be available in your command path.

   - Your PGP must be configured correctly. @{b}PGPPATH@{ub} and @{b}PGPPASS@{ub} have to
     be set properly. If you have problems with PGP leaving files in
     your @{b}UUSpool:@{ub}, check our if PGP's @{b}KeepBinary@{ub} option is turned off.


@EndNode

