@Node "PRM_What is it?" "PGP_MIP.guide/PRM_What is it?"
@Next "PRM_Installation"
@Toc "PGPRMail"

What is PGPRMail?
=================

    PGPRMail is a front-end for the UUCP command "rmail". PGPRMail is
just started @{i}before@{ui} "rmail" and recognizes mail, containing
PGP-encrypted blocks. These blocks are decrypted and inserted instead
of the encrypted part. The new mail will be delivered to "rmail" to
handle the folder-stuff.

The message will then look something like this: (1)

     From: foobar@pgp_mip_land.peti (Jow Dow)
     Subject: This is just a test...
     
     Hi Peti,
     
     ==== begin of decrypted PGP message ====
     Nothin' special.
     
     I just wanted to show the readers how a decrypted message will look
     like.
     ==== end of decrypted PGP message ====
     
             bye, Peter

    PGPRMail won't touch any keys (2) or messages that are not signed
or whose signature can't be validated. This is for security reasons, so
please do not modify this in the sources!

How does it work?
=================

    The inner workings of PGPRMail are quiete simple. When invoked, it
reads the complete message from standard input and copies it into a
temporary file. (3) Then this file is re-read line by line and scanned
for the @{b}----BEGIN PGP MESSAGE----@{ub} line. If PGPRMail finds this header,
it will copy the PGP block into another temporary file until the end of
the encrypted block is reached. (Damaged or incomplete blocks are
recognized and handled corretcly!) Then PGPRMail calls PGP to decrypt
the the message and inserts the result instead of the encrypted part in
the message.  If PGP returns any kind of error, the original message is
used furthermore!

    The previously described scan process is continued now, just in
case, the mail conatins several encrypted blocks.

    If PGPRMail finished this process without any errors, the modified
message is directed to "rmail" instead of the original, preserving the
commandline, PGPRMail has been called with.

    ---------- Footnotes ----------

    (1)  Please pay attention to the fact that unencrypted data will be
preserverd, including the complete message header.

    (2)  Keyhandling is way too important to let it happen
automatically! Sorry guys, but you'll have to read PGP's manual for
this part. ;-)

    (3)  This is for data-security reasons. Under any error condition
(say, PGPRMail runs out of memory), PGPRMail will use this unmodified
mail, this prevents data-loss!


@EndNode

@Node "PRM_Installation" "PGP_MIP.guide/PRM_Installation"
@Next "PRM_Configuration"
@Prev "PRM_What is it?"
@Toc "PGPRMail"

How to install PGPRMail into your UUCP site:
============================================

The installation is that simple, you won't believe it: :-)

   - Copy @{b}PGPRMail@{ub} somewhere into your commandpath, usually @{b}UUCP:c/@{ub} or
     @{b}UUCPC:@{ub}.

   - Now set the @{b}RMail@{ub}-entry in your UUCP master config file (1) to make
     programs like "uuxqt" call PGPRMail instead of the original rmail:

          RMail         UUCPC:rmail
          
          is modified to
          
          RMail         UUCPC:pgprmail

   - Check, if your additional programs, like mail- or newsreader use
     this config-entry. Some programs (AmigaELM for example) use their
     own configfile rather than the master file.

   - If you haven't set @{i}PGPPASS@{ui} yet, the time has come to do so, or
     PGPSendMail won't be able to encrypt anything. Please read PGP's
     manual for further details on @{i}PGPPASS@{ui}. See @{"Future releases" Link "PRM_Future releases"}.

    That's it! If your system has enough memory, you may make PGP and
PGPRMail resident, what should result in a significant speedup.

    If you have only a small amount of spare memory, you could assign
@{b}T:@{ub} to your harddisk (2), because all temporary file are created in
the @{b}T:@{ub}-directory. This would save some memory, while slowing your
system down.

    ---------- Footnotes ----------

    (1)  @{b}UULIB:Config@{ub} or @{b}S:UUConfig@{ub}

    (2)  Usually, @{b}T:@{ub} is assigned somewhere in the RAM-Disk for
speed-reasons.


@EndNode

